# Commit Review Rules

This file describes the process for reviewing commits using Cursor's Composer window (Cmd/Ctrl + L).

## Quick Review
Ask the Composer to "Review my last commit and run tests" and it will:
1. Show the changes in your last commit
2. Check for:
   - [ ] Commit message follows standards (see commits.rules)
   - [ ] Obvious errors or copy/paste mistakes
   - [ ] Test coverage adequacy
   - [ ] Documentation updates
   - [ ] Potential issues or bugs
3. Run tests by executing:
   ```bash
   ./gradlew testDebugUnitTest
   ```
4. Provide a final recommendation

### Review Format
The AI will use these emoji in its review:
- ✅ Pass: Requirement met
- ❌ Fail: Issue found
- ⚠️ Warning: Needs attention
- 🔍 Investigating: Needs more information

### Individual Commit Review Checklist
For each commit, the AI will verify and mark with emoji:
- [ ] Commit message follows standards defined in commits.rules
- [ ] No obvious copy/paste errors
- [ ] Code style is consistent
- [ ] No potential bugs or issues
- [ ] Tests are included where needed
- [ ] Documentation is complete
- [ ] No performance concerns
- [ ] No security issues

### Collective Review Checklist
The AI will review all commits together for:
- [ ] Overall coherence and progression
- [ ] Any breaking changes (marked with ! or footer)
- [ ] Migration requirements
- [ ] API consistency
- [ ] Dependency updates
- [ ] Database schema changes
- [ ] Consistent commit message style across all commits

### Final Review Summary
The AI will provide:
1. Overview of all changes
2. Test results (from running `./gradlew testAll`)
3. Commit message quality assessment
4. Suggested improvements
5. Push/don't push recommendation with emoji (✅/❌/⚠️)
6. Any follow-up tasks

## Settings
- Maximum files per review: 50
- Maximum lines per file: 500
- Ignored patterns:
  * *.lock
  * *.log
  * build/*
  * .gradle/*

## Example Composer Prompts
- "Review my last commit and run tests"
- "Review all my unpushed commits and run tests"
- "Check if my commits are ready to push to main"
- "Review my recent changes for any issues"
- "Check if my commit messages follow our standards"

## Best Practices
- Review commits one at a time first, then as a whole
- Pay special attention to files with many changes
- Look for patterns across multiple commits
- Always ensure tests pass before pushing
- Document any concerns or follow-up tasks
- Fix commit messages before pushing if they don't meet standards 